Introduction¶

TMDb Data Set :¶

  • This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb),including user ratings and revenue.
  • This data set contains : rows = 10866 , columns = 21
  • I am going to showcase my data cleaning, wrangling and visualisation (Exploratory Data Analysis) skills using pandas,numpy, matplotlib and seaborn libraries in this project.
In [2]:
# packages used
%matplotlib inline
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Data Wrangling¶

I am going to do the following steps:

  • Load the data set into a DataFrame.
  • Find the general Properties of the Data Set.
  • Find the duplicate rows and drop them.
  • Find the null values or odd characters present in specific columns and, either drop them or fill them with appropriate values(eg: mean).
  • Find the attributes which are not useful for extracting insights from our dataset and drop them.

Univariate Analysis¶

In [290]:
def uni_info (arg):
    print('mean of ',arg,': ',clean_df_tmdb[arg].mean())
    print('median of ',arg,': ',clean_df_tmdb[arg].median())
    print('standard deviation of ',arg,': ',clean_df_tmdb[arg].std())

As the standard deviation (popularity) is larger than mean (popularity)¶

Hence,The popularity variable's data is highly spread out which means high variation in data.¶

In [268]:
bin_edges = [2,3.5,4.5,5.5,6.5,7.5,8.5,9]
bin_names = ['low popularity','popularity 3+','popularity 4+','popularity 5+','mod_high popularity','popularity7+','high popularity']
pd.cut(clean_df_tmdb['popularity'],bin_edges,labels = bin_names).hist(figsize=(10,5));

Mean, Median and Standard Deviation of budget, revenue, vote_average and vote_count variables¶

  • Variation in data would be really high for budget,revenue and vote_count as the standard deviation is larger than the mean.
  • Budget = the distribution is Positively Skewed
  • Revenue = the distribution is Positively Skewed
  • Vote Average = the data is Normally Distributed
  • Vote Count = the distribution is Positively Skewed

Q7. Average Budget and Revenue Of Movies From Year To Year?¶

Between 1990 to 2000 there was a huge increase in the average budget of the movies, after that we can notice some fluctuations (decreasing trend).¶

In [134]:
def  avg_bud_rev(arg,color):
    x = clean_df_tmdb.groupby('release_year')[arg].mean()
    proportion = x/x.sum()
    proportion.plot(kind = 'line',figsize=(10,4.5),color = color,lw=0.7, marker='.');
    plt.xlabel('Release Year',fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel('Budget|Revenue',fontsize=14);
    plt.title('Average Budget and Revenue Of Movies From Year To Year',fontsize=18);
In [143]:
avg_bud_rev('budget','blue')
avg_bud_rev('revenue','red')
plt.legend(['budget','revenue']);

We can observe the trend of the Budget and Revenue is similar (They are related to each other).¶

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize = (16,6))
regplot('red','black','popularity',axes[0][0])

regplot('black','red','runtime',axes[1][0])
regplot('black','red','vote_average',axes[1][1])
  • Plot 1 High revenue vs popularity Correlation = 0.562961
  1. There is a strong positive correlation between movies having High Revenue and Popularity.
  2. We can say, if the popularity of a movie increases, the revenue of that movie may increase too.
  • Plot 2 High revenue vs budget Correlation = 0.632547
  1. There is a strong positive correlation here.
  2. This means, there's a possibility that High Revenue Movies have High Budget.
  • Plot 3 High revenue vs runtime Correlation = 0.196986
  1. There is no strong relationship of High Revenue Movies with Runtime.
  • Plot 4 High revenue vs vote_average Correlation = 0.243236
  1. There is a weak relationship of High Revenue Movies with Vote Average.
  2. Hence, Vote Average is not related to High Revenue Movies.

Q10. Which month of the year are most movies released?¶

Highest number of releases happen during the month of september.¶

Here I extracted the Months from the released_date variable and added it to a new column named months_number.

In [413]:
release = clean_df_tmdb.copy()
release['months_number'] = pd.to_datetime(release['release_date']).dt.strftime('%m')
In [428]:
plt_1 = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
x = ['jan','feb','march','april','may','june','july','august','september','october','november','december']
y =release.groupby('months_number')['imdb_id'].count()
plt.plot(x,y)
plt.title('Number of Releases per month',fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('months',fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('budget',fontsize=15)
plt.show()

Conclusions¶

  • "Thriller" was the most popular genre for majority of the years (1960 to 2015)
  • Highest Release of Movies were made in the year 2014.
  • Woody Allan has directed the highest number of movies (42 movies).
  • Number 1 Movie according to the ratings of the viewers is Pink Floyd:Pulse.
  • Least rated movie by the viewers is Manos: The Hands of Fate(1.5 rating).
  • Highest profit movie is "Avatar", following Star Wars: The Force Awakens and then Titanic.
  • Lowest profit movie is "The Warrior's Way".
  • The Audience prefer movies with long duration (100 to 200 mins or 2.5 to 2.8hrs).
  • Higher budget movies have higher average profit compared to lower budget movies.
  • Revenue is strongly related to the Budget.
  • Highest number of releases happen during the month of september.
  • Movies released in the month of May and June have the highest revenue compared to the other months.

Limitations¶

  • The currency of the budget and revenue were not specified in the documentation.
  • A column based on "The Movie Industry" would have been great for extracting better insights from the data set.
  • "The Movie Industry" would contain values like :

Hollywood,Bollywood,Chinese Cinema,United Kingdom of Great Britain,Japanese Cinema (Nihon Eiga), and many more.

  • There were many 0 values in the Variables : runtime,budget,revenue. Dropping these values must have affected our exploratory data analysis.
  • My analysis tells us what measures need to be taken for :

1) Making a profitable movie. 2) Understaning if a viewer should watch a specific movie or not.

Note:

The result of analysis process might not be completely error free.
